stration of 3dmodeling, so that you can more easily bring your projects to fruition. Email me at andrew@solidwize.com, any time.\r\n<h4 style=\"text-align: left;\">[/one_half_last]</h4>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"></p>','About','','inherit','open','open','','410-revision-7','','','2012-04-19 18:53:48','2012-04-20 01:53:48','',410,'http://solidwize.com/2012/410-revision-7',0,'revision','',0),(682,15,'2012-04-30 01:49:31','2012-04-30 08:49:31','','sae','','publish','closed','closed','','sae','','','2012-04-30 01:49:31','2012-04-30 08:49:31','',0,'http://solidwize.com/?page_id=682',0,'page','',0),(649,15,'2012-04-20 19:22:52','2012-04-21 02:22:52','','Solidworks Tutorials','','publish','closed','closed','','solidworkstutorials','','','2012-04-20 19:28:18','2012-04-21 02:28:18','',0,'http://solidwize.com/?page_id=649',0,'page','',0),(650,15,'2012-04-20 19:13:33','2012-04-21 02:13:33','','Auto Draft','','inherit','open','open','','649-revision','','','2012-04-20 19:13:33','2012-04-21 02:13:33','',649,'http://solidwize.com/2012/649-revision',0,'revision','',0),(651,15,'2012-04-20 19:22:52','2012-04-21 02:22:52','','Solidworks Tutorials','','inherit','open','open','','649-revision-2','','','2012-04-20 19:22:52','2012-04-21 02:22:52','',649,'http://solidwize.com/2012/649-revision-2',0,'revision','',0),(652,15,'2012-04-20 19:23:02','2012-04-21 02:23:02','','Solidworks Tutorials','','inherit','open','open','','649-revision-3','','','2012-04-20 19:23:02','2012-04-21 02:23:02','',649,'http://solidwize.com/2012/649-revision-3',0,'revision','',0),(653,15,'2012-04-20 18:08:35','2012-04-21 01:08:35','<h3 style=\"text-align: center;\">The Mission</h3>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Our mission here at Solidwize is very simple, to get you learning SolidWorks as quickly and efficiently as possible, so you can stop struggling and start creating killer products. We are a small team entirely dedicated to that end, and as such we are able to quickly createvaluablecontent each week based on the immediate needs of our customers. Our users are part of the family, so if you have any questions about our content, your projects, or anything else going on in your life, we\'d love to help -<a id=\"contact\" class=\"contactform\" title=\"Contact\" href=\"#\">email</a>, call (877.688.7563)or post in our new<a title=\"Community\" href=\"http://solidwize.com/questions\">community section</a>.We\'ll get back to you as soon as humanly possible.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3 style=\"text-align: center;\">The Team</h3>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center; margin-bottom: 30px;\">Just two dudes who are really passionate about SolidWorks, teaching people how to use it, and building great products.</p>\r\n[one_half]\r\n<h4 style=\"text-align: left; margin-bottom: 0px;\">Rohit Mitra</h4>\r\n<h5>Founder, Content Guy</h5>\r\nI got my start with SolidWorks after joining (and eventually becoming project lead) of my college\'s Baja SAE team while studying mechanical engineering. After I graduated, I went to work for SolidWorks for a time before moving to the largest SolidWorks reseller to work in a technical support capacity. The best part of my day was helping customers design projects they are passionate about, so I started SolidWize to do that full time. I\'d love to hear from you, email me directly at Rohit@solidwize.com or follow me on <a title=\"Solidwize Twitter\" href=\"http://twitter.com/solidwize\">twitter</a>.\r\n<h4 style=\"text-align: left;\">[/one_half]</h4>\r\n[one_half_last]\r\n<img class=\"wp-image-463 alignright\" title=\"me1\" src=\"http://solidwize.com/solidwize/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/me1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"298\" height=\"226\" />\r\n[/one_half_last]\r\n\r\n[one_half]\r\n<a href=\"http://solidwize.com/solidwize/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/andrewabout.jpg\"><img class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-643\" title=\"andrewabout\" src=\"http://solidwize.com/solidwize/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/andrewabout.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"298\" height=\"226\" /></a>\r\n\r\n[/one_half]\r\n[one_half_last]\r\n<h4 style=\"text-align: left; margin-bottom: 0px;\">Andrew O\'Neal</h4>\r\n<h5>Co-Founder, Biz Dev Guy</h5>\r\nOnce upon a time I worked for one of the largest talent agencies in entertainment. After becoming jaded to the whole industry, I returned to my Silicon Valley roots. My background is in product development and web marketing. I\'ve pushed several digital and physical products to market, and after watching Rohit use SolidWorks to model one of my projects, I realized the power of the incredible tool and decided to help him teach others how to use it. My deep hope is that we can help you remove the frustration of 3dmodeling, so that you can more easily bring your projects to fruition. Email me at andrew@solidwize.com, any time.\r\n<h4 style=\"text-align: left;\">[/one_half_last]</h4>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"></p>','About','','inherit','open','open','','410-revision-9','','','2012-04-20 18:08:35','2012-04-21 01:08:35','',410,'http://solidwize.com/2012/410-revision-9',0,'revision','',0),(656,2,'2012-04-11 14:59:00','2012-04-11 21:59:00','<a href=\"http://solidwize.com/solidwize/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/backbone_01.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-544\" title=\"backbone_01\" src=\"http://solidwize.com/solidwize/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/backbone_01.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"550\" height=\"369\" /></a>\r\n\r\nEven the most simple looking products, can present a problem when trying to recreate the same geometry within SolidWorks. If you are well versed with SolidWorks Sheet Metal, the chair shown above, from <a href=\"http://www.yankodesign.com/2012/04/04/skeletal-seating/\" title=\"Yanko Design\" target=\"_blank\"></a>,can be designed in several different manners, but if you\'re new to sheet metal tools, this may provide a bit of a conundrum. Because the part is self intersecting, the profile cannot be draw up in a single sketch. In my opinion, there are two simple methods in which to design this. You can draw the entire profile slightly modified, so that the profile does not self intersect, add a base flange and then add a bend and a few cuts to finish the part. The other option, and the one I chose, is to draw part of the profile to create a base flange from and then build off of that geometry. I wanted to use the side profile image of the chair to draw the profile, so this was the preferred method.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://solidwize.com/solidwize/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/skeletal-seating-step-1.png\"><img src=\"http://solidwize.com/solidwize/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/skeletal-seating-step-1.png\" alt=\"\" title=\"skeletal seating step 1\" width=\"550\" height=\"502\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-551\" /></a>\r\n\r\nUsing a sketch picture, I drew the profile in the above picture, except for the extension that passes through the hole in the part. Then an unfold feature was used in conjunction with a extruded cut and a mirror to get the two cutouts in the chair. \r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Skeletal Seating','','inherit','open','open','','543-revision-7','','','2012-04-11 14:59:00','2012-04-11 21:59:00','',543,'http://solidwize.com/2012/543-revision-7',0,'revision','',0),(657,2,'2012-04-26 16:30:31','2012-04-26 23:30:31','<a href=\"http://solidwize.com/2012/skeletal-seating\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-544\" title=\"backbone_01\" src=\"http://solidwize.com/solidwize/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/backbone_01.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"550\" height=\"369\" /></a>\r\n\r\nEven the most simple looking products, can present a problem when trying to recreate the same geometry within SolidWorks. If you are well versed with SolidWorks Sheet Metal, the chair shown above, from <a href=\"http://www.yankodesign.com/2012/04/04/skeletal-seating/\" title=\"Yanko Design\" target=\"_blank\"></a>,can be designed in several different manners, but if you\'re new to sheet metal tools, this may provide a bit of a conundrum. Because the part is self in