3\"]Most users will spend quite a bit of time using \"solid\" modeling techniques. This section will cover the basics of solid modeling and take you through the features, within SolidWorks, that apply to solid modeling. </br> </br>\r\n\r\nStart with the sketching section and reference geometries, so that you can effectively create your base sketches, and then jump to the section that is the most relevant to the parts that you model.\r\n\r\n[/ion_tab]\r\n\r\n[/ion_tabset]','Part Modeling','','inherit','open','open','','301-revision-15','','','2012-04-05 19:11:28','2012-04-06 02:11:28','',301,'http://solidwize.com/2012/301-revision-15',0,'revision','',0),(912,2,'2012-06-26 18:19:26','2012-06-27 01:19:26','<a href=\"http://solidwize.com/2012/mechanical-mates\"><img src=\"http://solidwize.com/solidwize/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/ford-powershift-gearbox12.jpg\" alt=\"\" title=\"ford-powershift-gearbox12\" width=\"550\" height=\"344\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-914\" /></a>\r\n\r\nThe standard mates in SolidWorks are great for fixing a part in place or simple sliding motion. If you want any sort of mechanical motion, you have to use the advanced mates or mechanical mates. The mechanical mates allow you to create the relationships listed in the picture below.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://solidwize.com/solidwize/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/mechanical-mates.png\"><img src=\"http://solidwize.com/solidwize/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/mechanical-mates.png\" alt=\"\"title=\"mechanical mates\" width=\"238\" height=\"267\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-917\" /></a>\r\nThe mechanical mates work in the following manner:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Cam Mate: a point or face to a cam profile or surface</li>\r\n	<li>Hinge Mate: create both a coincident and concentric relation in a single mate</li>\r\n	<li>Gear Mate: two circles such that the motion of one drives the motion of the other by a set ratio</li>\r\n	<li>Rack Pinon: same as gear mate except a circle drives a straight edge instead of another circle</li>\r\n	<li>Screw: as an object is turned about its axis, it also move linearly along that axis</li>\r\n	<li>Universal Joint: two axes rotate at the same rate as a universal joint would</li>\r\n\r\n\r\n</br>\r\nTo see how to create each mate, see the video below:\r\n\r\n<iframe width=\"550\" height=\"309\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/Oupme_s5uZg\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>','SolidWorks Assemblies: Mechanical Mates','','publish','open','open','','mechanical-mates','','','2012-06-26 18:19:26','2012-06-27 01:19:26','',0,'http://solidwize.com/?p=912',0,'post','',0),(913,15,'2012-04-05 18:49:14','2012-04-06 01:49:14','[ion_tabset tab1=\"Table of Contents\" tab2=\"Exercise Files\" tab3=\"Description\"]\r\n\r\n[ion_tab id=\"tab1\"][videodirectory id=\"18,21,20,19\"][/ion_tab]\r\n\r\n[ion_tab id=\"tab2\"]Download 2011 Fileset: <a href=\'http://solidwize.com/solidwize/wp-content/uploads/2012/01/3-Drawings-2011.zip\'>3 Drawings 2011</a>\r\n</br>\r\nDownload 2012 Fileset: <a href=\'http://solidwize.com/solidwize/wp-content/uploads/2012/01/3-Drawings-2012.zip\'>3 Drawings 2012</a>\r\n\r\n[/ion_tab]\r\n\r\n[ion_tab id=\"tab3\"]This section covers how to create drawings from your parts and assemblies. For most users the most important takeaway is how to create custom drawing templates and sheet formats. This will allow drawings to be standardized upon creation.</br></br>\r\n\r\nOther takeaways:</br>\r\n-How to create model views</br>\r\n-Annotating drawings</br>\r\n-Using tables to simplify design communication</br>\r\n[/ion_tab]\r\n\r\n[/ion_tabset]','Drawings','','inherit','open','open','','357-revision-11','','','2012-04-05 18:49:14','2012-04-06 01:49:14','',357,'http://solidwize.com/2012/357-revision-11',0,'revision','',0),(914,2,'2012-06-26 18:02:16','2012-06-27 01:02:16','','ford-powershift-gearbox12','','inherit','open','open','','ford-powershift-gearbox12','','','2012-06-26 18:02:16','2012-06-27 01:02:16','',912,'http://so